post_text: Welcome back West Prairie! First day of student attendance is August 19th. We are excited to start the new year and ready to see our students, both remotely and in person. This school year will certainly be different, and while we are faced with many new challenges, our teachers and staff will continue to do their best for the students of West Prairie. Have a great year!

post_text:
Thomas Haberle Memorial Fund/West Prairie School District Athletic Fund

On March 26, 2020, Thomas Haberle passed away unexpectedly from a heart attack. His family would like to honor him by setting up a memorial fund for West Prairie Athletics in his name. He loved watching his grandchildren participate in various sporting activities. Tom was a former teacher and coach for Colchester High School and now has two grandchildren that attend West Prairie. He was so proud of them and was always in the front row cheering them on. Tom valued the life lessons that sports teach the youth so we are honored to create this memorial in his name.

Checks can be mailed to the Unit Office @ 204 S. Hun Street in Colchester, IL 62326. Please note the Thomas Haberle Memorial in the check memo.

post_text: Emergency Food Response - In partnership with Loaves and Fishes, Genesis Garden is sending out free groceries to help out local families during the pandemic. Once a week we send milk, eggs, bread, frozen meat and many other groceries to families who sign up on our Facebook page. Right now we serve between 120 and 160 households throughout McDonough County but we have the capacity to help more. Here is the link to the sign up page. https://forms.gle/2eNuyuCtqggbfXJc7

post_text:
Parent to Parent tips for Remote Learning!

Have a routine! Do things the same way each day and at the same time. It does wonders for everyone!

Spend time each night after the kids are in bed (or each weekend) preparing their activities for the next day. Our girls have a hand written checklist in their notebook each day from me that helps them stay focused on what they need to do next. They love checking off things they finished and then can see how much is left to do.

We have a small plastic snack box for each child for the DAY. They pick 2 snacks for the day (1 has to be healthy), place them in the box along with their cup or water bottle. That helps with less dishes for the day and prevents them grazing all day long.

I tell my kids no electronics (except what they need for their schoolwork) during what would be the school day 8-3, just like if they were in school. If they get work done, they find other non - electronic things to do. It's a struggle some days, and sometimes there's a lot of pouting and arguing about it, but we stick to it.

post_text:
More Remote Learning tips from West Prairie parents.....Great advice...keep them coming!

I feel one reason our kids are succeeding during this time is because we have kept them on the same bedtime routines they had during actual school days. A good nights sleep is essential for a good day of learning.

Be calm and patient with your children, they are struggling too and this is new for everyone! If you see they are struggling or upset, give them a 15 minute break to regroup, before trying again!

Take lots of breaks! If you notice your child getting frustrated, go outside for an hour. Come back and try to attempt the work again. If you're frustrated your child will feel it too.

post_text:
West Prairie parents are sharing strategies to help with Remote Learning at home. Below are a couple of ideas that were shared today in the Family Check-In Survey.

Stay busy and keep things fun! Make chores or pickup time into a fun game or challenge!

Stay with a schedule in the home. If you are struggling with an assignment, walk away for a bit and come back to it.

Don't give the entire day's work at one time. Don't expect younger children to sit and complete all work at once. We give 1 paper task at a time and then give 'brain breaks' in between-like playing Legos, drawing/coloring, playing outside, etc.

McDonough County CEO Program
April 19 at 1:55 PM ·

We have gotten a bit behind in introducing you to our stellar mentors, but we are ready to get back at it! This intro comes from home-schooled junior, Jenna Nelson: "I'm super excited to introduce Rachel Kerns as my mentor! She grew up in McDonough County and graduated from West Prairie in 2014. Rachel is currently the director of marketing and public relations at McDonough Telephone Co-op located in Colchester. Her favorite part about her job is that she gets to help her company grow in new ways. Some of Rachel's hobbies include playing volleyball, reading, and travelling. She also loves playing with her cat Pumpkin and her dog Thor. Rachel is really excited to be a part of this program because she loves what it is teaching the students and how it is preparing them for the future". #mcdococeo #youngentrepreneurs #mentorship

People are creatures of habit and life gets difficult when things are out of routine. Times of uncertainty are stressful for all. Stress decreases when healthy routines are in place.

Please know that school counselors and social workers are on staff daily in West Prairie Schools. You can contact them best by using the email provided below. You can also call a school office and your call will be directed to the appropriate staff member.

West Prairie School Social Services
wpschoolservices@wp103.org

shared_text:
McDonough Esda
February 25 at 6:51 PM ·

Storm tonight downgraded.

Well, the good news is that it looks like it will be a repeat of this morning's storm.
The bad news news is that kids will likely have school tomorrow.
Not much accumulation as the storm kept moving away from us.
The National Weather Service is just advising caution as visibility and icy roads will be the main hazards overnight into the morning.
So far, snow will be mainly before 5am. Low around 26. North wind around 15 mph, with gusts as high as 25 mph. Snow accumulation of 1 to 2 inches possible.
